## Evidence tags

Every medical claim carries one of:

| Tag | Meaning |
|-----|---------|
| `[RCT]`  | Randomized controlled trial |
| `[META]` | Systematic review or meta-analysis of RCTs |
| `[OBS]`  | Observational, cohort, case-control |
| `[CASE]` | Case series or case report |
| `[REV]`  | Narrative review |
| `[CONS]` | Consensus statement / clinical guideline |
| `[MECH]` | Mechanism / preclinical / human provocation (sub-tag below) |
| `[SPEC]` | Speculation, AI-generated hypothesis, no primary citation |
| `[UNVERIFIED]` | Citation that failed round-trip — quarantine; do not use in clinician-facing output |

### Mechanism sub-tags

- `[MECH-human]` — human provocation or biomarker study (strongest)
- `[MECH-preclinical]` — animal / cell-line
- `[MECH-review]` — narrative mechanism review
- `[MECH-inference]` — extrapolation from related biology

### Applicability axis

When an evidence-tagged claim is intended to inform action on the
{{condition_name}} case at the center of this project, append an
applicability annotation:

```
[RCT; applicability: low — population excluded prior multi-class failure]
[META; applicability: moderate — refractory subgroup pooled but small]
```

Levels: `high` / `moderate` / `low` / `unknown`. A high-quality RCT can
be low-applicability if its population doesn't resemble the case at hand
— e.g. trial enrollment criteria excluded the comorbidity profile, the
prior-treatment-failure history, or the disease severity that defines
this project. Note exclusions explicitly when they matter.

### Citation verified ≠ claim verified

Citation round-trip (PMID/DOI lookup) confirms a paper exists with the
cited title and authors. It does **not** confirm the paper says what we
cited it for. Stronger than `[SPEC]` requires a verbatim quote (or close
paraphrase) anchored in `literature/papers/{PMID}.md`'s "Quote bank,"
sourced from the abstract or fetched section.

The subtle hallucination is **claim drift** — citing a real paper for a
stronger / narrower / different claim than it actually makes. The
quote-anchor protects against this; round-trip alone does not.

The full round-trip protocol — when to fetch, what to record in the
paper note, how to mark a failed verification, and how to handle
disagreement between sources — lives in `meta/research-methodology.md`.
That file is the operational companion to this one; the tag definitions
here only have force when the round-trip discipline there is applied.

## Lead lifecycle

Every thread (cause hypothesis, treatment candidate, open question,
diagnostic probe) eventually ends in one of:

- **clinician-discussion candidate** — ready to bring to the specialist
- **ruled out** — actively decided against, with rationale
- **waiting on data** — needs tracker / clinical / lab data first
- **waiting on lit verification** — needs paper round-trip
- **watchlist** — keep monitoring; revisit if landscape changes
- **dead end** — exhausted, no further action

A thread in none of these states is open work-in-progress. That's fine
when the project is small; revisit if active threads exceed ~5 and
threads are getting lost.

## Treatment-history adequacy categories

Every entry in `treatments/tried.md` and `intake/treatments.md` should
classify as exactly one of:

- **adequate failure** — full duration + dose / intensity per the
  benchmarks below, no response, no intolerable adverse event
- **inadequate trial** — stopped before benchmark for any reason
- **intolerable** — stopped due to adverse event before efficacy could
  be judged
- **partial response** — measurable improvement below responder
  threshold, possibly worth retaining or combining
- **tachyphylactic response** — clear initial response, durable loss
- **confounded** — efficacy could not be judged due to concurrent
  changes (other med start/stop, illness, life event, overuse pattern)
- **unclear** — incomplete data, can't classify (record what's missing)
- **never tried**

This taxonomy is the input to the why-not-standard-ladder rule in
`CLAUDE.md`: a treatment is candidate-worthy only if its prior history
is `inadequate trial`, `intolerable`, `partial response`,
`tachyphylactic response`, `unclear`, or `never tried` — or if there is
some other rationale beyond efficacy in the broader population.

